<p>I was searching for a solution on how to include floating elements in their container (by default, they fall out of it if it's too short). I found the answer on Stackoverflow to set <code>overflow</code> to <code>hidden</code> for the container and indeed it worked. But my question is: why? Spec for <code>overflow: hidden</code> on w3cschools states:</p>  <blockquote>   <p>This value indicates that the content is clipped and that no scrolling user interface should be provided to view the content outside the clipping region.</p> </blockquote>  <p>So I'd rather expect the part of the float to be clipped than the container to be extended to include the float. Which rule applies here?</p>  <hr />  <p>Example:</p>  <p><div class="snippet" data-lang="js" data-hide="false"> <div class="snippet-code"> <pre class="snippet-code-html lang-html prettyprint-override"><code>    &lt;div style="border: 1px solid black;"&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Ala ma kota&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;div style="float: right; width: 200px; height: 200px; border: 1px solid red;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;</code></pre> </div> </div> </p>  <p>And fixed:</p>  <p><div class="snippet" data-lang="js" data-hide="false"> <div class="snippet-code"> <pre class="snippet-code-html lang-html prettyprint-override"><code>    &lt;div style="border: 1px solid black; overflow: hidden;"&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Ala ma kota&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;div style="float: right; width: 200px; height: 200px; border: 1px solid red;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;</code></pre> </div> </div> </p>